        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We propose to obtain Band 7 observations of CO(3-2) from the filamentary cold gas located in the centre of NGC 4636. We request a single pointing at 345 GHz using the FDM mode with 1.875 GHz bandwidth. We aim to achieve a spatial resolution of at least 0.5 arcsec, probing radii close to the Bondi accretion radius of the central SMBH. We do not aim to look at CO(3-2) emission on extended scales and therefore we will not require the Compact Array. 

ALMA’s exquisite sensitivity is necessary in order to discover emission from molecular gas in this system; to date, no reliable detection of CO emission from the filamentary optical line emitting nebula around NGC4636 is available. However, our detection of [CII] line emission with Herschel PACS gives us firm reason to expect the presence of molecular gas in this region.

The peak [CII] flux measured with Herschel PACS is 13 Jy, with a line width of 361 km/s (Werner et al. 2013). If the ionization mechanism in the filamentary gas surrounding NGC4636 and the central group galaxy NGC5044 is the same, then using the [CII] to CO(2-1) flux ratio measured in NGC5044 (Werner et al. 2013b) and assuming a CO(3-2)/CO(2-1) ratio of 2 yields an expected peak flux density of 5.2 mJy. Because the Halpha/[CII] flux ratio is fairly uniform in NGC5044, we can use an Halpha map to simulate the expected CO emission.

The best high resolution image of the nebula is an Halpha+[NII] image from the SOAR telescope, which also shows a good agreement with the [CII] flux distribution. We rescaled this Halpha image to a range of expected peak fluxes and performed a series of simulations using CASA’s simobserve and simanalyze tools. 

Based on these simulations, we request a target RMS sensitivity of 0.17 mJy per beam per 50 km/sec (binned) channel, which can be reached in 3 hours on source.  Over the expected range of CO(3-2) flux density per beam, an RMS sensitivity of 0.17 mJy will enable a S/N of 3 - 25 per 30 km/sec velocity element.
 
In the most likely scenario that the [CII] to CO flux conversion is similar to that measured in NGC 5044, we will be able to sample the filament along the SE loop (the faintest feature we aim to study in detail) in 30 km/s resolution elements with a S/N of 5. However, the uncertainty in the flux conversion between [CII] and CO is potentially large. This ratio is about a factor of 4 smaller in normal galaxies and Galactic molecular clouds (amounting to a higher CO flux for a fixed [CII] line intensity) than in starburst galaxies and Galactic star-forming regions (Crawford et al. 1985; Stacey et al. 1991). Even in the most pessimistic scenario that the [CII] to CO is among the highest values ever measured in any other galaxy, we will still detect the bright central part of NGC4636 with a S/N of at least 10 per 30 km/sec velocity element.</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
